# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baba-vida
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman military, musical instruments such as the *tuba* (a long trumpet) or the *cornu* were used to give various commands, while the *buccina* (possibly a trumpet or horn) and the *lituus* (probably an elongated J-shaped instrument), were used in ceremonial capacities.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Music was used in the Roman amphitheatres between fights and in the *odea*, and in these settings is known to have featured the *cornu* and the *hydraulis* (a type of water organ).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Most religious rituals featured musical performances.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some music historians believe that music was used at almost all public ceremonies.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The graffiti, brothels, paintings, and sculptures found in Pompeii and Herculaneum suggest that the Romans had a sex-saturated culture.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Latin literature was, from its start, influenced heavily by Greek authors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some of the earliest extant works are of historical epics telling the early military history of Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] As the Republic expanded, authors began to produce poetry, comedy, history, and tragedy.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome's literary contributions are still recognised today and the works by ancient Roman authors were available in bookshops as well as in public and private libraries.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Many scholars and statesmen of ancient Rome cultivated private libraries that were used both as demonstrations of knowledge and displays of wealth and power.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Although Julius Caesar had intended to establish public libraries to further establish Rome as a great cultural center like Athens and Alexandria, he died before this was accomplished.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Caesar's former lieutenant, Gaius Asinius Pollio, took up the project and opened the first public library in Rome in the Atrium Libertatis.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Emperors Augustus, Tiberius, Vespasian, Domitian, and Trajan also founded or expanded public libraries in Rome during their reigns.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] These included the Ulpian Library in Trajan's Forum and libraries in the Temple of Apollo Palatinus, the Temple of Peace in the Roman Forum, the Temple of Divus Augustus, which was dedicated to Minerva when it was rebuilt under Emperor Domitian's orders.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the city of Rome had more than two dozen public libraries.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] As the Roman Empire spread, public libraries were established in other major cities and cultural centers including Ephesos, Athens, and Timgad.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Roman cuisine changed over the long duration of this ancient civilisation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Dietary habits were affected by the influence of Greek culture, the political changes from Kingdom to Republic to Empire, and the Empire's enormous expansion, which exposed Romans to many new, provincial culinary habits and cooking techniques.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the beginning the differences between social classes were relatively small, but disparities evolved with the Empire's growth.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Men and women drank wine with their meals.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman diet included many items that are staples of modern Italian cooking.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] However, some foods now considered characteristic of modern Italian cuisine were not used.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In particular, spinach and eggplant (aubergine) were introduced later from the Arab world, and tomatoes, potatoes, capsicum peppers, and maize (the modern source of polenta) only appeared in Europe following the discovery of the New World and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans knew of rice, but it was very rarely available to them.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Butcher's meat such as beef was an uncommon luxury.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The most popular meat was pork, especially sausages.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Fish was more common than meat, with a sophisticated aquaculture and large-scale industries devoted to oyster farming.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also engaged in snail farming and oak grub farming.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some fish were greatly esteemed and fetched high prices, such as mullet raised in the fishery at Cosa, and "elaborate means were invented to assure its freshness".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, a breakfast called *ientaculum* was served at dawn.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At mid-day to early afternoon, Romans ate *cena*, the main meal of the day, and at nightfall a light supper called *vesperna*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] With the increased importation of foreign foods, the *cena* grew larger in size and included a wider range of foods.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, it gradually shifted to the evening, while the *vesperna* was abandoned completely over the course of the years.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The mid-day meal *prandium* became a light meal to hold one over until *cena*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The toga, a common garment during the era of Julius Caesar, was gradually abandoned by all social classes of the Empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At the early 4th century, the toga had become just a garment worn by senators in Senate and ceremonial events.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] At the 4th century, the toga was replaced by the *paenula* (a garment similar to a poncho) as the everyday garment of the Romans, from the lower classes to the upper classes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Another garment that was popular among the Romans in the later years of the Western Roman Empire was the *pallium*, which was mostly worn by philosophers and scholars in general.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Due to external influences, mainly from the Germanic peoples, the Romans adopted tunics very similar to those used by the Germanic peoples with whom they interacted in the final years of the Western Empire, also adopted trousers and hats like the *pileus pannonicus*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] During the Late Empire, the *paludamentum* (a type of military clothing) was used only by the Emperor of Rome (since the reign of Augustus, the first emperor) while the dalmatic (also used by the Christian clergy) began to spread throughout the empire.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The youth of Rome had several forms of athletic play and exercise.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Play for boys was supposed to prepare them for active military service, such as jumping, wrestling, boxing, and racing.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the countryside, pastimes for the wealthy also included fishing and hunting.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also had several forms of ball playing, including one resembling handball.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Dice games, board games, and gamble games were popular pastimes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] For the wealthy, dinner parties presented an opportunity for entertainment, sometimes featuring music, dancing, and poetry readings.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The majority, less well-off, sometimes enjoyed similar parties through clubs or associations, but for most Romans, recreational dining usually meant patronising taverns.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Children entertained themselves with toys and such games as leapfrog.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Public games and spectacles were sponsored by leading Romans who wished to advertise their generosity and court popular approval; in Rome or its provinces, this usually meant the emperor or his governors.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Venues in Rome and the provinces were developed specifically for public games.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Rome's Colosseum was built in 70 AD under the Roman emperor Vespasian and opened in 80 AD to host other events and gladiatorial combats.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Gladiators sometimes fought to the death, but more often to an adjudicated victory, usually in keeping with the mood of the watching crowd.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Shows of exotic animals were popular in their own right; but sometimes animals were pitted against human beings, either armed professionals or unarmed criminals who had been condemned to public death.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Chariot racing was extremely popular among all classes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, these races were usually held at the Circus Maximus, which had been purpose-built for chariot and horse-racing and, as Rome's largest public place, was also used for festivals and animal shows.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome boasted impressive technological feats, using many advancements that were lost in the Middle Ages and not rivalled again until the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] An example of this is insulated glazing, which was not invented again until the 1930s.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Many practical Roman innovations were adopted from earlier Greek designs.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were often divided and based on craft.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Artisans guarded technologies as trade secrets.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Roman civil engineering and military engineering constituted a large part of Rome's technological superiority and legacy, and contributed to the construction of hundreds of roads, bridges, aqueducts, public baths, theatres and arenas.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Many monuments, such as the Colosseum, Pont du Gard, and Pantheon, remain as testaments to Roman engineering and culture.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans were renowned for their architecture, which is grouped with Greek traditions into "Classical architecture".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Although there were many differences from Greek architecture, Rome borrowed heavily from Greece in adhering to strict, formulaic building designs and proportions.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Aside from two new orders of columns, composite and Tuscan, and from the dome, which was derived from the Etruscan arch, Rome had relatively few architectural innovations until the end of the Republic.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] In the 1st century BC, Romans started to use Roman concrete widely.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Concrete was invented in the late 3rd century BC.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] It was a powerful cement derived from pozzolana, and soon supplanted marble as the chief Roman building material and allowed many daring architectural forms.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Also in the 1st century BC, Vitruvius wrote *De architectura*, possibly the first complete treatise on architecture in history.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also largely built using timber, causing a rapid decline of the woodlands surrounding Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] It is suggested that timber, around 4 metres (13 ft) long, came up to Rome via the Tiber River on ships travelling across the Mediterranean Sea from the confluence of the Saône and Rhône rivers in what is now the city of Lyon in present-day France.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] With solid foundations and good drainage, Roman roads were known for their durability and many segments of the Roman road system were still in use a thousand years after the fall of Rome.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The construction of a vast and efficient travel network throughout the Empire dramatically increased Rome's power and influence.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] They allowed Roman legions to be deployed rapidly, with predictable marching times between key points of the empire, no matter the season.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] These highways also had enormous economic significance, solidifying Rome's role as a trading crossroads—the origin of the saying "all roads lead to Rome".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman government maintained a system of way stations, known as the *cursus publicus*, and established a system of horse relays allowing a dispatch to travel up to 80 km (50 mi) a day.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans constructed numerous aqueducts to supply water to cities and industrial sites and to aid in their agriculture.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] By the third century, the city of Rome was supplied by 11 aqueducts with a combined length of 450 km (280 mi).
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also made major advancements in sanitation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Romans were particularly famous for their public baths, called *thermae*, which were used for both hygienic and social purposes.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Many Roman houses had flush toilets and indoor plumbing, and a complex sewer system, the *Cloaca Maxima*, was used to drain the local marshes and carry waste into the Tiber.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have speculated that lead pipes in the sewer and plumbing systems led to widespread lead poisoning, which contributed to fall of Rome; however, lead content would have been minimised.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Ancient Rome is the progenitor of Western civilisation.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] The customs, religion, law, technology, architecture, political system, military, literature, languages, alphabet, government and many factors and aspects of western civilisation are all inherited from Roman advancements.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] The rediscovery of Roman culture revitalised Western civilisation, playing a role in the Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] The two longest ancient accounts of the Roman history, the histories of Livy and Dionysius of Halicarnassus, were composed 500 years later than the date for the founding of the republic and 200 years from the defeat of Hannibal.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Although there has been a diversity of works on ancient Roman history, many of them are lost.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] As a result of this loss, there are gaps in Roman history, which are filled by unreliable works, such as the **Historia Augusta**.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Caesar wrote his own accounts of his military campaigns in Gaul and during the Civil War in part to impress his contemporaries.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] In the Empire, the biographies of famous men and early emperors flourished, examples being *The Twelve Caesars* of Suetonius, and Plutarch's *Parallel Lives*.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Other major works of Imperial times were that of Livy and Tacitus.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Interest in studying, and idealising, ancient Rome became prevalent during the Italian Renaissance.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Edward Gibbon's *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* "began the modern study of Roman history in the English-speaking world".
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] Barthold Georg Niebuhr was a founder of the examination of ancient Roman history and wrote *The Roman History*, tracing the period until the First Punic War.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] During the Napoleonic, *The History of Romans* by Victor Duruy highlighted the Caesarean period popular at the time.
[src:baba-vida/ancient-rome-p03] *History of Rome*, *Roman constitutional law* and *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*, all by Theodor Mommsen, became milestones.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The **Anevo Fortress** (Bulgarian: Аневско кале, *Anevsko kale*) or **Kopsis** (Копсис) is a medieval castle in central Bulgaria, the ruins of which are located some 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) from the village of Anevo in Sopot Municipality, Plovdiv Province.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] Constructed in the first half of the 12th century, it lies on a steep hilltop at the southern foot of the Balkan Mountains, not far from the Stryama river.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] In the end of the 13th century, the fortress was the capital of a small short-lived quasi-independent domain ruled by the brothers of Tsar Smilets of Bulgaria, Voysil and Radoslav.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The hill where the Anevo Fortress is situated has been populated since no later than Antiquity (3rd–1st century BC), with habitation also evident throughout the Ancient Roman (1st–4th century), early Byzantine (5th–6th century) and Bulgarian (11th–14th century) periods of rule.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The castle reached its heyday in the last quarter of the 13th century, when under the rule of the Bulgarian nobles (*bolyari*) Voysil and Radoslav it was the capital of a quasi-independent realm.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The domain comprised the landholdings of the two renegade brothers of Tsar Smilets, which lay between the Balkan Mountains and Sredna Gora, approximately from modern Sliven west to Kopsis.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The Anevo Fortress is dominated by its fortified inner city or citadel, surrounded by defensive walls with gates and towers.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] In total, the Anevo Fortress is thought to have had eight defensive towers, of which only several have been preserved.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The towers are either rectangular or polygonal in shape, and their ruins reach up to 12 metres (39 feet) in height.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The western wall of the castle, flanked by a tower at each end, is in best condition.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The walls were constructed according to the *opus emplectum* technology out of broken local stones and river stones welded together by means of white mortar.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] Residential buildings within the citadel were generally built of broken stones and white mortar and had most often one, though in some cases two or more floors.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] The foundations of four churches have been unearthed: two of those lay in the citadel and the remaining two were located outside of it.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] At least one of the churches boasts preserved traces of medieval frescoes and pavement.
[src:baba-vida/anevo-fortress] Pottery has also been discovered at the Anevo Fortress.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The **Asara Fortress** (Bulgarian: крепост Асара) is a medieval stronghold located about a kilometer southwest from the village Zvezdel in Kardzhali Province of southern Bulgaria.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] This fortress played a crucial role in defending the land of the Eastern Rhodopes.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The fortress was built between the 11th and 12th centuries and occupied a strategically advantageous location on a rock sanctuary, which also featured a rock tomb from the mid-13th century BC to the 7th-6th centuries BC.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] This fortification included two rectangular towers on the western and eastern sides, while a wooden palisade encircled the northern and southern perimeters.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The eastern side was fortified with one of two square towers that guarded the entrance to the fortress.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The lower floor of this tower was designed as a water reservoir, with its base coated in hydrophobic pink mortar.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] Additionally, a 20 cm layer of purified sand was found, indicating a filtration system for the water.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The floor was intentionally sloped in one corner to facilitate the drainage of precipitation.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] In contrast to more common fortifications in the region, the majority of the fortress walls were constructed from wood, a notable rarity in Bulgaria, and particularly at the time the fortress was constructed.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The two towers were linked by a rock passageway.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] Within one of the towers, a chapel was discovered, along with remnants of murals.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The fortress was primarily tasked with overseeing and protecting the Zvezdel Mine, which at the time extracted gold and silver.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] Among the significant archaeological finds were an icon embellished with gold leaf and various bone medallions, some of which are now exhibited at the Regional History Museum in Kardzhali.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] The fortress is believed to have fallen during the Bulgarian-Byzantine wars of 1205–1207.
[src:baba-vida/asara-fortress] Its commanding position, exceptional visibility, and natural defenses made it a crucial asset for Byzantine control over the Eastern Rhodopes.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The earliest archaeological findings date from the time of the Thracians, the area of the fortress being also inhabited during the Ancient Roman and Early Byzantine period.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The fortress gained importance in the Middle Ages, first mentioned in the statute of the Bachkovo Monastery as *Petrich* in the 11th century.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The fortress was conquered by the armies of the Third Crusade.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] In 1205 the Latin Duke of Philippopolis, Renier of Trit, fled from Philippopolis, which was under pressure from Tsar Kaloyan of Bulgaria, and took refuge in Asen's Fortress (at the time called Stanimaka).
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] Renier of Trit would be besieged in the fortress for eleven months with just 40 knights before being relieved by the army of Latin Emperor Henry of Flanders.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] It was considerably renovated in the 13th century (more precisely 1231) during the rule of Bulgarian tsar Ivan Asen II to serve as a border fortification against Latin raids, as evidenced by an eight-line wall inscription.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The foundations of fortified walls—the outer ones being 2.9 metres (9.5 ft) thick and preserved up to a height of 3 metres (10 ft), originally 9 to 12 metres (30 to 39 ft) high—a feudal castle, 30 rooms and 3 water repositories have been excavated from this period.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The best preserved and most notable feature of Asen's Fortress is the Church of the Holy Mother of God from the 12th-13th century.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] It is a two-storey cross-domed single-naved building with a wide narthex and a large rectangular tower, and features mural paintings from the 14th century.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] In the following years after Ivan Assen II's death the castle switched hands between the Bulgarians and Byzantines for decades.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The fortress was once again in Bulgarian hands at the time of Ivan Alexander in 1344 only to be conquered and destroyed by the Ottomans during their rule of Bulgaria.
[src:baba-vida/asen-s-fortress] The town of Asenovgrad, formerly called *Stanimaka*, takes its modern name from the fortress.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The construction of the castle began in the 10th century at the place of the ancient Roman castell Bononia.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The building of Baba Vida is tied to a legend, according to which a Danubian Bulgarian king who ruled at Vidin had three daughters: Vida, Kula, and Gamza.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Prior to his death, he divided his realm among the three.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Vida, the eldest, was given Vidin and the lands north to the Carpathians, Kula was awarded Zaječar and the Timok Valley, and Gamza was to rule the lands west up to the Morava.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Although Gamza and Kula married to drunkard and warlike nobles, Vida remained unmarried and built the castle in her city.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The name of the castle means "Granny Vida".
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Baba Vida served as part of Vidin's main defensive installation during the course of the Middle Ages and acted as the citadel of the most important fortress of northwestern Bulgaria.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The Baba Vida stronghold withstood an eight-month-long siege by Byzantine forces led by Basil II.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] It was enlarged and modernized during the rule of tsar Ivan Stratsimir (1356–1396), as whose capital it served.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Between 1365 and 1369, the castle was in Hungarian hands.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Vidin was suddenly attacked by the forces of Louis I of Hungary, but it took several months to conquer Baba Vida.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] In 1369, Ivan Sratsimir managed to regain control of his capital, albeit having to remain under Hungarian overlordship.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] In 1388, the Ottomans invaded Sratsimir's lands and forced him to become their vassal.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] In 1396, he joined an anti-Ottoman crusade led by the King of Hungary, Sigismund, placing his resources at the crusaders' disposal.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The crusade ended in the disastrous Battle of Nicopolis at Nikopol, Bulgaria, with the Ottomans capturing most of Sratsimir's domains shortly thereafter, in 1397.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] The castle played a role during the Ottoman rule of Bulgaria, serving as a weapon warehouse and a prison, also as residence for Osman Pazvantoğlu, and it has been no longer used for defensive purposes since the end of the 18th century.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Today, Baba Vida castle functions as a museum.
[src:baba-vida/baba-vida] Being a popular tourist attraction, the castle is being kept in repair.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The early years of Basil's reign were dominated by civil wars against two powerful generals from the Byzantine Anatolian aristocracy: first Bardas Skleros and later Bardas Phokas, which ended shortly after Phokas' death and Skleros' submission in 989.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil then oversaw the stabilization and expansion of the eastern frontier of the Byzantine Empire and the complete subjugation of the First Bulgarian Empire, its foremost European foe, after a long struggle.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although the Byzantines had made a truce with the Fatimid Caliphate in 987–988, Basil led a campaign against the Caliphate that ended with another truce in 1000.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He also conducted a campaign against the Khazar Khaganate that gained the Byzantine Empire part of Crimea and led a series of successful campaigns against the Kingdom of Georgia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Despite near-constant warfare, Basil distinguished himself as a capable ruler, reducing the power of the great land-owning families who dominated the administration and military, filling its treasury, and leaving the Empire at its greatest territorial extent in four centuries.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although his successors were largely incompetent, the Empire flourished for decades after Basil's death.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] One of the most important decisions taken during his reign was to offer the hand of his sister Anna Porphyrogenita to Vladimir I of Kiev in exchange for military support, thus forming the Byzantine military unit known as the Varangian Guard.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The marriage of Anna and Vladimir led to the Christianization of the Kievan Rus' and the incorporation of later successor states of Kievan Rus' within the Byzantine cultural and religious tradition.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil is seen as a Greek national hero but is a despised figure among Bulgarians.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The courtier and historian Michael Psellos, who was born towards the end of Basil's reign, gives a description of Basil in his *Chronographia*.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Psellos describes him as a stocky man of shorter-than-average stature who nevertheless was an impressive figure on horseback.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He had light-blue eyes, strongly arched eyebrows, luxuriant side whiskers—which he had a habit of rolling between his fingers when deep in thought or angry—and in later life a scant beard.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Psellos also states that Basil was not an articulate speaker and had a loud laugh that convulsed his whole frame.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil is described as having ascetic tastes and caring little for the pomp and ceremony of the Imperial court, typically wearing a sombre, dark-purple robe furnished with few of the gems that usually decorated imperial costumes.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He is also described as a capable administrator who left a well-stocked treasury upon his death.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil supposedly despised literary culture and affected scorn for the learned classes of Byzantium.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He was a *porphyrogennetos* ("born into the purple"), as were his father Romanos II and his grandfather Constantine VII; this was the appellation used for children who were born to a reigning emperor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil was the eldest son of Romanos and his Laconian Greek second wife Theophano, who was the daughter of a poor tavern-keeper named Krateros and may have originated from the city of Sparta.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He may have had an elder sister named Helena (born c.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Romanos succeeded Constantine VII as sole emperor upon the latter's death in 959.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's father crowned him as co-emperor on 22 April 960, and his brother Constantine (born 960 or 961, eventually to rule as sole emperor Constantine VIII in 1025–1028) in 962 or 963.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Only two days after the birth of his youngest child Anna, Romanos II died on 15 March 963 at 24 years of age.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] His unexpected death was commonly thought at the time to be the result of poisoning with hemlock; the chroniclers Leo the Deacon and John Skylitzes imply that Theophano was responsible, and according to Skylitzes, she had been complicit in an earlier attempt by Romanos II to poison Constantine VII.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil and Constantine were too young to rule in their own right when Romanos died in 963.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Therefore, although the Byzantine Senate confirmed them as emperors with their mother as the nominal regent, *de facto* power passed for the time into the hands of the *parakoimomenos* Joseph Bringas.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Theophano did not trust Bringas, however, and another enemy of the powerful *parakoimomenos* was Basil Lekapenos, an illegitimate, eunuch son of Emperor Romanos I – Basil's great-grandfather.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Lekapenos himself had been *parakoimomenos* to Constantine VII and *megas baioulos* to Romanos II.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Yet another enemy of Bringas was the successful and widely popular general Nikephoros Phokas, who had just returned from his conquest of the Emirate of Crete and a highly successful raid into Cilicia and Syria, which culminated in the sack of Aleppo.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Phokas was proclaimed emperor by his men in July and marched on Constantinople.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bringas tried to bring in troops to stop his rival's advance, but the capital's populace supported Nikephoros.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bringas fled, leaving his post to Lekapenos, and on 16 August 963 Nikephoros Phokas was crowned emperor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] On 20 September, Phokas married Theophano, but problems resulted; it was a second marriage for each spouse and Nikephoros was thought to be the godfather of one or both of Theophano's sons.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although Polyeuctus, the patriarch of Constantinople, disapproved of the marriage, the Church declared it to be valid.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] With it, Nikephoros secured his legitimacy and became the guardian of Basil and Constantine.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He was murdered in December 969 by Theophano and his nephew John Tzimiskes, who then became emperor John I and exiled Theophano.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] John married Theodora, a sister of Romanos II.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil II acceded to the throne as effective ruler and senior emperor when John died on 10 January 976.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He immediately had his mother brought back from her convent.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil was a very successful soldier on horseback and through his achievement he proved himself to be an able general and a strong ruler.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In the early years of his reign, administration remained in the hands of Basil Lekapenos.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] As president of the Byzantine Senate, Lekapenos was a wily, gifted politician who hoped the young emperors would be his puppets.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The younger Basil waited and watched without interfering, devoting himself to learning the details of administrative business and military science.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Nikephoros II and John I were brilliant military commanders but proved to be poor administrators.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At the start of his reign, the failures of his immediate predecessors left Basil II with a serious problem: Bardas Skleros and Bardas Phokas, members of the wealthy military elite of Anatolia, had sufficient means to undertake open rebellion against his authority.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Skleros and Phokas, both of whom were experienced generals, wanted to assume the Imperial position that Nikephoros II and John I had held, and thus return Basil to the role of impotent cypher.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil, showing a penchant for ruthlessness, took to the field himself and suppressed the rebellions of both Skleros (979) and Phokas (989) with the help of 12,000 Georgians of Tornikios and David III Kuropalates of Tao.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The fall of Lekapenos occurred between the rebellions in 985; he was accused of plotting with the rebels and was punished with exile and the confiscation of his property.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The relationship between the two generals was complicated; Phokas was instrumental in defeating the rebellion of Skleros but when Phokas later rebelled, Skleros returned from exile to support him.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] When Phokas died in battle, Skleros, whom Phokas had imprisoned, assumed the leadership of the rebellion.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's brother Constantine—who had no interest in politics, statecraft, or the military–led troops alongside Basil; this was the only military command Constantine would hold.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The campaign ended without combat when Skleros was forced to surrender to Basil in 989.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Skleros was allowed to live but he died blind, either through disease or from being blinded as punishment for his insurrection.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] These rebellions had a profound effect on Basil's outlook and methods of governance.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Psellos describes the defeated Skleros giving Basil the following advice, which he took to heart: "Cut down the governors who become over-proud.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Let no generals on campaign have too many resources.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Exhaust them with unjust exactions, to keep them busied with their own affairs.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Admit no woman to the imperial councils.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] To defeat these dangerous revolts, Basil formed an alliance with Prince Vladimir I of Kiev, who in 988 had captured Chersonesos, the Empire's main base in the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Vladimir offered to evacuate Chersonesos and to supply 6,000 of his soldiers as reinforcements to Basil.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In exchange, he demanded to be married to Basil's younger sister Anna.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Byzantines viewed all of the peoples of Northern Europe—namely Franks and Slavs—as barbarians.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Anna objected to marrying a barbarian ruler because such a marriage would have no precedent in Imperial annals.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Vladimir had researched various religions, having sent delegates to various countries.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Marriage was not his main reason for choosing Christianity.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] When Vladimir promised to baptize himself and to convert his people to Christianity, Basil finally agreed.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Vladimir and Anna were married in Crimea in 989.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Rus' warriors taken into Basil's army were instrumental in ending the rebellion; they were later organized into the Varangian Guard.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This marriage had important long-term implications, marking the beginning of the process by which the Grand Duchy of Moscow many centuries later would proclaim itself "The Third Rome", and claim the political and cultural heritage of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Once the internal strife was quelled, Basil turned his attention to the Empire's other enemies.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Byzantine civil wars had weakened the Empire's position in the east, and the gains of Nikephoros II and John I had nearly been lost to the Fatimid Caliphate.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This lasted until the long-time vizier Yaqub ibn Killis died in 991.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Fatimid caliph Al-Aziz Billah chose to pursue a more aggressive stance in Syria and appointed Manjutakin as governor of Damascus.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Encouraged by the defectors after the death of emir Sa'd al-Dawla, Al-Aziz decided to renew his attacks on the Hamdanid Emirate of Aleppo, a Byzantine protectorate, perhaps expecting Basil would not interfere.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Manjutakin invaded the emirate, defeated a Byzantine force under the *doux* of Antioch Michael Bourtzes in June 992, and laid siege to Aleppo.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In early 993, after thirteen months of campaigning, a lack of supplies forced Manjutakin to return to Damascus.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 994, Manjutakin resumed his offensive and in September scored a major victory at the Battle of the Orontes against Bourtzes.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bourtzes' defeat forced Basil to intervene personally in the East; with his army, he rode through Asia Minor to Aleppo in sixteen days, arriving in April 995.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's sudden arrival and the exaggeration of his army's strength circulating in the Fatimid camp caused panic in the Fatimid army, especially because Manjutakin, expecting no threat, had ordered his cavalry horses to be dispersed around the city for pasture.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Despite having a considerably larger and well-rested army, Manjutakin was at a disadvantage.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He burned his camp and retreated to Damascus without battle.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Byzantines besieged Tripoli unsuccessfully and occupied Tartus, which they refortified and garrisoned with Armenian troops.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Al-Aziz now prepared to take to the field in person against the Byzantines and initiated large-scale preparations but they were abandoned upon his death.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Warfare between the two powers continued as the Byzantines supported an anti-Fatimid uprising in Tyre.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 998, the Byzantines under Damian Dalassenos, the successor of Bourtzes, launched an attack on Apamea but the Fatimid general Jaysh ibn al-Samsama defeated them in battle on 19 July 998.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This defeat drew Basil back into the conflict; he arrived in Syria in October 999 and remained there for three months.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's troops raided as far as Heliopolis, placed a garrison at Larissa, and burnt three minor forts in the vicinity of Abu Qubais, Masyath and Arca.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The siege of Tripoli in December failed while Emesa was not threatened.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's attention was diverted to developments in Georgia following the murder of David III Kuropalates; he departed for Cilicia in January and dispatched another embassy to Cairo.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1000, a ten-year truce was concluded between the two states.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] For the remainder of the reign of Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah (r.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] 996–1021), relations remained peaceful as al-Hakim was more interested in internal affairs.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Al-Hakim's persecution of Christians in his realm and especially the 1009 destruction of the Church of the Holy Sepulchre at his orders strained relations and, along with Fatimid interference in Aleppo, provided the main focus of Fatimid–Byzantine diplomatic relations until the late 1030s.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil sought to restore former territories of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At the start of the second millennium, he fought Samuel of Bulgaria, his greatest adversary.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bulgaria had been partly subjugated by John I after the invasion of Svyatoslav I of Kiev but parts of the country had remained outside Byzantine control under the leadership of Samuel and his brothers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Because the Bulgars had been raiding Byzantine lands since 976, the Byzantine government sought to cause dissension among them by allowing the escape of their captive emperor Boris II of Bulgaria.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This ploy failed so Basil used a respite from his conflict with the nobility to lead a 30,000-strong army into Bulgaria and besiege Sredets (Sofia) in 986.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Taking losses and worried about the loyalty of some of his governors, Basil lifted the siege and returned for Thrace but he fell into an ambush and suffered a serious defeat at the Battle of the Gates of Trajan.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil escaped with the help of his Varangian Guard and attempted to recover his losses by turning Samuel's brother Aron against him.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Aron was tempted by Basil's offer of his sister Anna in marriage, but the negotiations failed when Aron discovered the bride he was sent was an imposter.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Another brother of Samuel, called David, was killed in 976 by the Vlachs, the guards of caravans, between Prespa and Kastoria.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although the titular emperor Roman of Bulgaria was captured in 991, Basil lost Moesia to the Bulgarians.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] While Basil was distracted with internal rebellions and recovering the military situation on his eastern frontier, Samuel had extended his rule from the Adriatic Sea to the Black Sea, recovering most of the territory that was controlled by Bulgaria before the invasion of Svyatoslav.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He also conducted damaging raids into Byzantine territory as far as central Greece.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 996, the Byzantine general Nikephoros Ouranos defeated a Bulgarian army raid at the Battle of Spercheios in Thessaly.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Samuel and his son Gabriel narrowly escaped capture.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Beginning in 1000, Basil was free to focus on a war of conquest against Bulgaria, which he fought with grinding persistence and strategic insight.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1000, the Byzantine generals Nikephoros Xiphias and Theodorokanos took the former Bulgarian capital Great Preslav, and the towns Lesser Preslav and Pliskova.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1001, Basil, operating from Thessalonica, regained control of Vodena, Verrhoia and Servia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The following year, he based his army in Philippopolis and occupied the length of the military road from the western Haemus Mountains to the Danube, cutting off communications between Samuel's Macedonian heartland and Paristrion (the lands south of the lower Danube).
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Following this success, Basil laid siege to Vidin, which fell after a prolonged resistance.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Samuel reacted to the Byzantine campaign by launching a large-scale raid into the heart of Byzantine Thrace and took the major city of Adrianople by surprise.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] After turning homeward with his extensive plunder, Samuel was intercepted near Skopje by a Byzantine army commanded by Basil, whose forces stormed the Bulgarian camp, defeating the Bulgarians and recovering the plunder from Adrianople.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Skopje surrendered shortly after the battle, and Basil treated its governor Romanos with overt kindness.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1005, the governor of Dyrrhachium Ashot Taronites surrendered his city to the Byzantines.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The defection of Dyrrhachium completed the isolation of Samuel's core territories in the highlands of western Macedonia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Samuel was forced into an almost entirely defensive stance; he extensively fortified the passes and routes from the coastlines and valleys held by the Byzantines to the territory remaining in his possession.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] During the next few years, the Byzantine offensive slowed and no significant gains were made, although an attempt by the Bulgarians to counter-attack in 1009 was defeated at the Battle of Kreta, to the east of Thessalonica.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1014, Basil was ready to launch a campaign aimed at destroying Bulgarian resistance.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] On 29 July 1014, in the Battle of Kleidion, he and his general Nikephoros Xiphias outmaneuvered the Bulgarian army, which was defending one of the fortified passes.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Samuel avoided capture through the valor of his son Gabriel.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Having crushed the Bulgarians, Basil exacted his vengeance cruelly—he was said to have captured 15,000 prisoners and fully blinded 99 of every 100 men, leaving one one-eyed man in each cohort to lead the rest back to their ruler.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] A possible reason for this vengeance was that, in Byzantine eyes, the Bulgarians were rebels against their authority, and blinding was the usual punishment meted out to rebels.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Samuel was struck down by the sight of his blinded army and died two days later on 6 October 1014 after suffering a stroke.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bulgaria fought on for four more years, its resistance fired by Basil's cruelty, but it submitted in 1018.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This submission was the result of continued military pressure and a successful diplomatic campaign aimed at dividing and suborning the Bulgarian leadership.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This victory over the Bulgarians and the later submission of the Serbs fulfilled one of Basil's goals; the Empire regained its ancient Danubian frontier for the first time in 400 years.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The rulers of neighbouring Croatia, Krešimir III and Gojslav, who were previously allies of Bulgaria, accepted Basil's supremacy to avoid the same fate as Bulgaria; Basil warmly received their offers of vassalage and awarded them the honorary title of *patrikios*.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Croatia remained a tributary state to Basil until his death in 1025.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Before returning to Constantinople, Basil celebrated his triumph in Athens.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He showed considerable statesmanship in his treatment of the defeated Bulgarians, giving many former Bulgarian leaders court titles, positions in provincial administration, and high commands in the army.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In this way, he sought to absorb the Bulgarian elite into Byzantine society.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Because Bulgaria did not have a monetary economy to the same extent as Byzantium, Basil decided to accept Bulgarian taxes in kind.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's successors reversed this policy, a decision that led to considerable Bulgarian discontent and rebellion later in the 11th century.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although the Kievan Rus' had broken the power of the Khazar Khaganate in the 960s, the Byzantines had not been able to fully exploit the power vacuum and restore their dominion over Crimea and other areas around the Black Sea.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1016, Byzantine armies in conjunction with Mstislav of Chernigov attacked the Crimea, much of which had fallen under the control of the Khazar successor kingdom of George Tzoul based at Kerch.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Kedrenos reports that Tzoul was captured and the Khazar successor kingdom was destroyed.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Subsequently, the Byzantines occupied southern Crimea.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The integrity of the Byzantine Empire was threatened after a full-scale rebellion led by Bardas Skleros broke out in 976.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] After winning a series of battles, the rebels conquered Asia Minor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In the urgency of the situation, Georgian prince David III of Tao aided Basil; after a decisive loyalist victory at the Battle of Pankaleia, he was rewarded by lifetime rule of key imperial territories in eastern Asia Minor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] David's rebuff of Basil in Bardas Phokas' revolt of 987, however, evoked Constantinople's distrust of the Georgian rulers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] After the revolt's failure, David was forced to make Basil the legatee of his extensive possessions.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1001, after the death of David of Tao, Basil inherited Tao, Phasiane and Speri.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] These provinces were then organized into the theme of Iberia with the capital at Theodosiopolis.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This forced the successor Georgian Bagratid ruler Bagrat III to recognize the new rearrangement.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bagrat's son George I, however, inherited a longstanding claim to David's succession.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] George, who was young and ambitious, launched a campaign to restore the Kuropalates's succession to Georgia and occupied Tao in 1015–1016.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He entered in an alliance with the Fatimid caliph of Egypt, al-Hakim, forcing Basil to refrain from an acute response to George's offensive.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Byzantines were also involved in a relentless war with the Bulgarians, limiting their actions to the west.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] As soon as Bulgaria was conquered in 1018 and al-Hakim was dead, Basil led his army against Georgia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Preparations for a larger-scale campaign against the Kingdom of Georgia were set, beginning with the re-fortification of Theodosiopolis.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In late 1021, Basil, at the head of a large Byzantine army reinforced by the Varangian Guard, attacked the Georgians and their Armenian allies, recovering Phasiane and continuing beyond the frontiers of Tao into inner Georgia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] King George burned the city of Oltisi to prevent it falling to the enemy and retreated to Kola.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] A bloody battle was fought near the village Shirimni at Lake Palakazio on 11 September; the emperor won a costly victory, forcing George I to retreat northwards into his kingdom.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil plundered the country and withdrew for winter to Trebizond.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Several attempts to negotiate the conflict failed.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] George received reinforcements from the Kakhetians and allied himself with the Byzantine commanders Nikephoros Phokas Barytrachelos and Nikephoros Xiphias in their abortive insurrection in the emperor's rear.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In December, George's ally the Armenian king Senekerim of Vaspurakan, who was being harassed by the Seljuk Turks, surrendered his kingdom to the emperor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] During early 1022, Basil launched a final offensive, defeating the Georgians at the Battle of Svindax.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Menaced both by land and sea, George agreed to a treaty that handed over Tao, Phasiane, Kola, Artaan and Javakheti, and left his infant son Bagrat as Basil's hostage.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 992, Basil concluded a treaty with the Doge of Venice Pietro II Orseolo under terms reducing Venice's custom duties in Constantinople from 30 *nomismata* to 17 *nomismata*.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In return, the Venetians agreed to transport Byzantine troops to southern Italy in times of war.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] According to one estimate, a Byzantine landowning farmer might expect a profit of 10.2 *nomismata* after paying dues for half of his best-quality land.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil was popular with the country farmers, the class that produced most of his army's supplies and soldiers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] To assure this continued, Basil's laws protected small agrarian property owners and lowered their taxes.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Despite the almost constant wars, Basil's reign was considered an era of relative prosperity for the class.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Seeking to protect the lower and middle classes, Basil made ruthless war upon the system of immense estates in Asia Minor—which his predecessor Romanos I had endeavored to check—by executing a legal decree in January 996 that limited rights to property ownership.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] If the owner of an estate could prove that he claimed his estate prior to the Novels of Romanos, he would be allowed to keep it.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] If a person had illegally seized an estate following the Novels of Romanos, he would have his rights to the estate declared null and the legal owners could reclaim it.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1002, Basil also introduced the *allelengyon* tax as a specific law obliging the *dynatoi* (wealthy landholders) to cover for the arrears of poorer tax-payers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Though it proved unpopular with the wealthier sections of Byzantine society, Basil did not abolish the tax; the emperor Romanos III abolished the *allelengyon* in 1028.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] By 1025, Basil—with an annual revenue of 7 million *nomismata*—was able to amass 14.4 million *nomismata* (or 200,000 pounds/90 tonnes of gold) for the Imperial treasury due to his prudent management.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Despite his attempts to control the power of the aristocracy, they again took control of the government following his death.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil II was praised by his army because he spent most of his reign campaigning with it rather than sending orders from Constantinople, as had most of his predecessors.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] This allowed his army to be largely supportive of him, often making his stance in political and church matters unquestionable.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He lived the life of a soldier to the point of eating the same daily rations as the rest of the army.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He also took the children of dead army officers under his protection and offered them shelter, food and education.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Many of these children became his soldiers and officers, taking the places of their fathers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] One of them, Isaac Komnenos, later became emperor himself.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The exact size of the army under Basil II is unknown, but estimates put it as high as 110,000 men, excluding the imperial *tagmata* in Constantinople; a considerable force, compared with the nominal establishment force of c.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At the same time, however, under Basil the practice began of relying on allied states—most notably Venice—for naval power, beginning the slow decline of the Byzantine navy during the 11th century.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil II later secured the annexation of the sub-kingdoms of Armenia and a promise that its capital and surrounding regions would be willed to Byzantium following the death of its king Hovhannes-Smbat.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1021, he also secured the cession of the Kingdom of Vaspurakan by its king Seneqerim-John, in exchange for estates in Sebasteia.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil created a strongly fortified frontier in those highlands.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Other Byzantine forces restored much of Southern Italy, which had been lost during the previous 150 years.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil was preparing a military expedition to recover the island of Sicily when he died on 15 December 1025, having had the longest reign among any Byzantine or Roman emperor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At the time of his death, the Empire stretched from southern Italy to the Caucasus and from the Danube to the Levant, which was its greatest territorial extent since the Muslim conquests four centuries earlier.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil was to be buried in the last sarcophagus available in the rotunda of Constantine I in the Church of the Holy Apostles but he later asked his brother and successor Constantine VIII to be buried in the Church of St.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] John the Theologian (*i.e.*, the Evangelist) at the Hebdomon Palace complex outside the walls of Constantinople.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The epitaph on Basil's tomb celebrated his campaigns and victories.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] In 1260, during the unsuccessful Nicean Byzantine siege of Constantinople, then held by the Latin Empire, a corpse was found, upright in a corner of the Church of St.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] John the Evangelist, with a shepherd's flute placed in its mouth.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] An inscription allowed the Nicaean soldiers to identify the corpse as the remains of Basil II.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The body of Basil II was transferred to the Monastery of the Saviour at Selymbria.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The following year, Constantinople was recovered by the Byzantines.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil II's reign is one of the most significant in Byzantine history.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] His constant military campaigns led to the zenith of Byzantine power in the Middle Ages.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The restoration of the Danubian frontier helped establish a more stable and secure border for the empire in Europe, maintaining a stronger barrier against Hungarian and Pecheneg raiders.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The conquest of Bulgaria and the submission of the South Slavs created relative peace for the empire's Balkan lands, keeping larger cities—including Constantinople—safe from the previously frequent sieges and looting.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's military experience that allowed him to eventually turn the war against Bulgaria in the Byzantine Empire's favor were gained through the revolts of Phokas and Skleros in Anatolia that challenged his throne and sometimes got close to deposing him.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil's creation of the Varangian Guard provided him and his successors with an elite mercenary force capable of changing battle outcomes and boosting morale that became feared by the emperor's enemies.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At this time, the Macedonian Renaissance was taking effect, seeing the rise of classical Greek scholarship being assimilated into Christian art and the study of ancient Greek philosophy being widespread.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The studies of these subjects, and the enlargement projects of the emperors, greatly expanded the library of the University of Constantinople, which again established itself as the main source of learning for its day.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Though he was not a man of literature, Basil was a relatively pious ruler who involved himself in the construction of churches, monasteries and, to some extent, cities.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Literary works, eulogies and poems were made by the great cities of the Byzantine Empire that mostly tried to juxtapose the classic past of kingdoms and empires with the new expansion of Basil II in which he was compared with many important figures of the east such as Cyrus the Great and Artaxerxes.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He was also particularly compared with Alexander the Great who was believed to be Basil's ancestor.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Classical works such as "The Persians" by the ancient Greek tragedian Aeschylus were among the most recited in the empire during the expansion given the different confrontations against the caliphates that the Byzantines indiscriminately and classically called "Medes".
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Basil II lacked heirs due to the "dearth of cousins found within the Macedonian dynasty", so he was succeeded by his brother Constantine and his family, who proved to be ineffective rulers.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Nevertheless, fifty years of prosperity and intellectual growth followed because the funds of state were full, the borders were safe from intruders, and the Empire remained the most powerful political entity of the age.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] At the end of Basil II's reign, the Byzantine Empire had a population of approximately 12 million people.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Although they were beneficial, Basil's achievements were reversed very quickly.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Many of the Georgian, Armenian and Fatimid campaigns were undone after the succession crisis and eventual civil war after the Battle of Manzikert in 1071.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Because many of the empire's governors went to the capital with their soldiers to seize power after the capture of emperor Romanos IV, the Anatolian frontier was largely left undefended against the Seljuk Empire.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Normans permanently pushed the Byzantines from Southern Italy in April 1071.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] According to the 19th-century historian George Finlay, Basil saw himself as "prudent, just, and devout; others considered him severe, rapacious, cruel, and bigoted.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] For Greek learning he cared little, and he was a type of the higher Byzantine moral character, which retained far more of its Roman than its Greek origin".
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The modern historian John Julius Norwich wrote of Basil: "No lonelier man ever occupied the Byzantine throne.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] And it is hardly surprising: Basil was ugly, dirty, coarse, boorish, philistine and almost pathologically mean.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] He cared only for the greatness of his Empire.
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] No wonder that in his hands it reached its apogee".
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] Bulgarian commentator Alexander Kiossev wrote in *Understanding the Balkans*: "The hero [of] a nation might be the villain of its neighbour ...
[src:baba-vida/basil-ii] The Byzantine emperor Basil the Murderer of Bulgarians, a crucial Greek pantheon figure, is no less important as [a] subject of hatred for our national mythology".
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The **Battle of Nicopolis** took place on 25 September 1396 and resulted in the rout of an allied Crusader army, assisted by the Venetian navy, at the hands of an Ottoman force, raising the siege of the Danubian fortress of Nicopolis and leading to the end of the Second Bulgarian Empire.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] It is often referred to as the **Crusade of Nicopolis**, as it was one of the last major Crusades of the Middle Ages, together with the Crusade of Varna in 1443–1444.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] By their victory at Nicopolis, the Turks discouraged the formation of European coalitions against them.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] They maintained their pressure on Constantinople, tightened their control over the Balkans, and became a greater threat to Central Europe.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] There were many minor crusades in the 14th century, undertaken by individual kings or knights.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Most recently there had been a failed crusade against Tunisia in 1390, and there was ongoing warfare in northern Europe along the Baltic coast.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] After the Battle of Kosovo in 1389, the Ottomans had conquered most of the Balkans and had reduced the Byzantine Empire to the area immediately surrounding Constantinople, which they blockaded from 1394 on.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In 1393 the Bulgarian tsar Ivan Shishman had lost Nicopolis — his temporary capital — to the Ottomans, while his brother, Ivan Stratsimir, still held Vidin but had been reduced to an Ottoman vassal.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In the eyes of the Bulgarian boyars, despots, and other independent Balkan rulers, the crusade was a great chance to reverse the course of the Ottoman conquest and take back the Balkans from Islamic rule.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In addition, the front line between Islam and Christianity had been moving slowly towards the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Kingdom of Hungary was now the frontier between the two religions in Eastern Europe, and the Hungarians were in danger of being attacked themselves.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Republic of Venice feared that Ottoman control of the Balkan peninsula, which included Venetian territories like parts of Morea and Dalmatia, would reduce their influence over the Adriatic Sea, Ionian Sea, and Aegean Sea.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Genoese also owned the citadel of Galata, located at the north of the Golden Horn in Constantinople, to which Bayezid had laid siege in 1395.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In 1394, Pope Boniface IX proclaimed a new crusade against the Turks, although the Western Schism had split the papacy in two, with rival popes at Avignon and Rome, and the days when a pope had the authority to call a crusade were long past.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The two decisive factors in the formation of the last crusade were the ongoing Hundred Years' War between Richard II's England and Charles VI's France and the support of Philip II, Duke of Burgundy.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In 1389, the war had ground to one of its periodic truces.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Further, in March 1395, Richard II proposed a marriage between himself and Charles VI's daughter Isabella in the interests of peace and the two kings met in October 1396 on the borders of Calais to agree to the union and agree to lengthen the Truce of Leulinghem.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The support of Burgundy, among the most powerful of the French nobles, was also vital.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In 1391, Burgundy, trying to decide between sending a crusade to either Prussia or Hungary, sent his envoy Guy de La Trémoille to Venice and Hungary to evaluate the situation.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Burgundy originally envisioned a crusade led by himself and the Dukes of Orléans and Lancaster, though none would join the eventual crusade.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] It was very unlikely that defense against the Turks was considered a particularly important goal of the crusade.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In August, Sigismund's delegation of four knights and a bishop arrived in the court of Paris to paint a description of how "40,000" Turks were despoiling and imperiling Christian lands and beg, on Sigismund of Hungary's behalf, for help.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Charles VI, having secured a peace with England through the marriage of his daughter, was able to reply that it was his responsibility to protect Christianity and punish Sultan Bayezid.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] French nobility responded enthusiastically to the declaration; Philip of Artois, Count of Eu, the Constable of France, and Jean II Le Maingre, the Marshal of France, declared participation in the crusade the duty of every "man of valor".
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Another major participant was John I, future Duke of Burgundy and Count of Nevers at the time.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] He was one of the principal leaders of the French forces sent to aid in the war.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] John's bravery during the battle earned him the cognomen Fearless (*Sans-Peur*).
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] According to the Chronica Hungarorum, King Sigismund of Hungary was so delighted at the sight of the large army gathered around him in Buda, he exclaimed in joy: "Who would be so bold as to dare to resist us?
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The number of combatants is heavily contested in historical accounts.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The oft-given figure of 100,000 crusaders is dismissed by Tuchman, who claims that 100,000 men would have taken a month to cross the Danube at Iron Gate, while the crusaders took eight days.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] From France, it was said about 5,000 knights and squires joined, and were accompanied by 6,000 archers and foot soldiers drawn from the best volunteer and mercenary companies; totalling some 11,000 men.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Next in importance were the Knights Hospitaller of Rhodes, who were the standard bearers of Christianity in the Levant since the decline of Constantinople and Cyprus.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Venice supplied a naval fleet for supporting action, while Hungarian envoys encouraged German princes of the Rhineland, Bavaria, Saxony, and other parts of the empire to join.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] French heralds had proclaimed the crusade in Poland, Bohemia, Navarre, and Spain, from which individuals came to join.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Italian city-states were too much engaged in their customary violent rivalries to participate, and the widely reported and acclaimed English participation never actually occurred.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The report of 3,000 English knights comes from contemporary Antonio Fiorentino, and was taken as fact by historian Aziz S.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A thousand knights would have actually amounted to "four to six thousand men and at least twice as many horses", counting foot-soldiers and other retainers.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] However, there are no records of financial arrangements being made in England to send a force abroad, nor of any royal preparation needed to organize and dispatch such a force.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Atiya also thought that the invocation of St.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] George as a war cry at Nicopolis signified the presence of English soldiers, for whom George was a patron saint; but Froissart, who mentions this, claims that the cry was made by the French knight Philippe d'Eu.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Furthermore, there was no collection of ransom money in England to pay for captives, as there was in every other country that had sent men to the battle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sporadic mention in contemporary accounts of the presence of "English" may be attributed to Knights Hospitaller of the English langue subgrouping, who joined their comrades for the crusade after leaving Rhodes (where the Hospitallers were based at the time) and sailing up the Danube.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevertheless, obviously inflated figures continue to be repeated.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] These result in a figure of about 47,000–49,000 in total; possibly up to 120,000 or 130,000 according to numerous sources, including the Ottoman historian Şükrullah who, in the 1460s, gives the figure of the crusader army as 130,000 in his *Behçetu't-Tevârih*.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The strength of the Ottoman forces is also estimated at 15–20,000; but inflated figures are common here as well.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Numerous sources provide estimates of the size of the army as up to 60,000 including the Ottoman historian Şükrullah, who, writing in the 1460s, gives the figure of the Ottoman army as 60,000 in his *Behçetu't-Tevârih*; alternately described as roughly half of the Crusader army.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Ottoman force also included 1,500 Serbian heavy cavalry knights under the command of Prince Stefan Lazarević, who was Sultan Bayezid's brother-in-law and vassal since the Battle of Kosovo in 1389.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] However, Burgundy retained control of the enterprise he was funding by naming 24-year-old John, Count of Nevers, the Duke's eldest son, for nominal command.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The ambiguity of the crusaders' command structure would prove to be crucial in the outcome.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] While Nevers was given a long list of "counselors", as well as another list of prominent French lords on the crusade with whom Nevers could consult "when it seemed good to him", the concept of unity of command was not yet embraced by medieval warriors.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The crusade set forth from Dijon on 30 April 1396, heading to Bavaria by way of Strasbourg via the upper Danube, from where they used river transport to join with Sigismund in Buda.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] From there the crusader goals, though lacking details of planning, were to expel the Turks from the Balkans and then go to the aid of Constantinople, cross the Hellespont, and march through Turkey and Syria to liberate Palestine and the Holy Sepulchre, before returning in triumph to Europe by sea.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Arrangements were made for a fleet of Venetian vessels to blockade the Turks in the Sea of Marmara and for the Venetians to sail up the Danube to meet the crusaders in Wallachia in July.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Coucy was not with the crusader body as it traveled, having been detached on a diplomatic mission to Gian Galeazzo Visconti, the Duke of Milan.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Furious at French political maneuvering that had removed Genoa from his influence, Gian Galeazzo had been attempting to stop the transfer of Genoese sovereignty to France and Coucy was dispatched to warn him that France would consider further interference a hostile act.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Valentina Visconti, the wife of the Duke of Orleans and Gian Galeazzo's beloved daughter, had been exiled from Paris due to the machinations of Queen Isabeau the same month as the departure of the crusade.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Duke of Milan threatened to send knights to defend his daughter's honor but, in the wake of the disaster at Nicopolis, it was widely believed that he had relayed intelligence to Bayezid I of crusader troop movements.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] There is no firm evidence of this and it is likely that Gian Galeazzo became a scapegoat after the fact due to the existing animosity with France, though there remains the possibility that the Duke of Milan, who had murdered his own uncle to ensure his own power, did in fact betray the crusaders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Croatian forces led by Ban Nicholas II Garai moved towards Buda from the coastal town of Nin in June, following a session of the Croatian Parliament, and joined the royal Hungarian army led by Sigismund.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Coucy arrived well before Nevers, who had stopped in the upper Danube for receptions and festivities thrown by German princes.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevers did not arrive in Vienna until 24 June, a full month behind the crusader vanguard led by d'Eu and Boucicaut.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A fleet of 70 Venetian vessels loaded with provisions was sent down the Danube, while Nevers enjoyed yet more parties thrown by his brother-in-law Leopold IV, Duke of Austria.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevers then asked his brother-in-law for a staggering loan of 100,000 ducats, which took time to arrange, and eventually arrived in Buda in July.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Once the leaders had arrived, strategy had to be coordinated with Philibert de Naillac, Master of the Knights Hospitaller, and representatives of the Venetian fleet.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Forty-four Venetian ships had carried the Hospitallers from Rhodes through the Aegean into the Sea of Marmara, and some continued into the Black Sea and up the Danube without engaging in battle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The fact that the Turks, who had an inferior naval presence, did not challenge the Venetians for control of the sea is seen as evidence that Bayezid and the majority of his forces were already on the European side.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The War Council in Buda was immediately the forum of a fierce dispute.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The previous year, Bayezid had declared that he would attack Hungary by May, yet he had not appeared by end of July.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Hungarian scouts sent out as far as the Hellespont could find no sign of him, causing the French to proclaim that he was a coward.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund of Hungary assured the crusaders that Bayezid would come, and advised that it would be wiser to let the Turks make the long march to them, rather than make the same long march to find them.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] This strategy was rejected by the French and their allies.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The crusaders began to march down the left bank of the Danube, though part of the Hungarian army veered north to gather the forces of Transylvania and the Mircea the Elder-led forces of Wallachia.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The remainder of the Hungarians brought up the rear of the crusader column.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] As the crusaders moved into Muslim-held territory, pillaging and mistreatment of the population reportedly grew.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] While crusaders had been reported to engage in periodic pillage and raping while passing through Germany, the indiscipline of the French reportedly reached new heights when they entered "schismatic" lands.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Chroniclers also waxed eloquent on the immorality and blasphemy of the crusaders, writing detailed accounts of drunkard knights lying with prostitutes for days, despite writing from at best second-hand accounts.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Tuchman cautions that such chroniclers were part of a contemporary tendency to blame the defeat of the crusade on the immorality of the crusaders, and that it is impossible to verify such claims.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At Orşova, where the Danube narrows at the Iron Gates gorge, the column crossed to the right bank using pontoons and boats over eight days.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Their first target was Vidin, previously the capital of Western Bulgaria and then under Turkish control.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The ruler of Vidin, Ivan Sratsimir of Bulgaria, having no desire to fight for his Turkish conquerors against an overwhelming force of crusaders, promptly surrendered.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The only bloodshed was the execution of Turkish officers in the defending garrison, though the incident served to further convince the French that Turks were incapable of challenging the crusaders in the field.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The next target was Oryahovo (Rachowa), a strong fortress located 75 miles (121 km) from Vidin.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Frustrated by the lack of opportunity to show their bravery in deeds of arms, the French carried out a forced march at night to reach the castle before their allies, arriving in the morning just as the Turkish forces had come out to destroy the bridge across the moat.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In fierce combat the French secured the bridge but were unable to push forward until Sigismund arrived.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The forces combined and managed to reach the walls before night forced the combatants to retire.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The next morning the inhabitants of Oryahovo agreed to surrender to Sigismund on the assurance that their lives and property would be spared.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The French promptly broke Sigismund's agreement, pillaging and massacring the town after the gates were open, and later claiming that they had taken the town by conquest because their men-at-arms had topped the walls the night before.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A thousand residents, both Turkish and Bulgarian, were taken hostage and the town set ablaze.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Hungarians took the French action as a grave insult to their king, while the French accused the Hungarians of trying to rob them of the glory of victory through combat.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Leaving a garrison to hold Oryahovo, the crusaders continued towards Nicopolis, assaulting one or two forts or settlements along the way, but bypassing one citadel from which messengers escaped to inform Bayezid of the Christian army.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] On 12 September the crusaders came within view of the fortress of Nicopolis on its limestone cliff.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nicopolis, located in a natural defensive position, was a key stronghold controlling the lower Danube and lines of communication to the interior.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A small road ran between the cliff and river, while the fortress was actually two walled towns, the larger one on the heights on the cliff and the smaller below.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Further inland from the fortified walls, the cliff sloped steeply down to the plain.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Well-defended and well-supplied, the Turkish governor of Nicopolis, Doğan Bey, was certain that Bayezid would have to come to the aid of the town and was prepared to endure a long siege.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The crusaders had brought no siege machines with them, but Boucicaut optimistically stated that ladders were easily made and worth more than catapults when used by courageous men.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] However, the lack of siege weapons, the steep slope up to the walls and the formidable fortifications made taking the castle by force impossible.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The crusaders set up positions around the town to block the exits, and with the naval blockade of the river, settled in for a siege to starve out the defenders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevertheless, they were convinced that the siege of the fortress would be a mere prelude to a major thrust into relieving Constantinople and did not believe that Bayezid I would arrive so speedily to give them a real battle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Two weeks passed as the bored crusaders entertained themselves with feasts, games, and insulting the martial prowess of their enemy.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Whether through drunkenness or carelessness, the crusaders posted no sentries, though foragers venturing away from the camps brought word of the Turks' approach.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Bayezid was at this time already through Adrianople and on a forced march through the Shipka Pass to Tirnovo.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] His vassal Stefan Lazarević of Serbia joined him on the way.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund had sent 500 horsemen to carry out reconnaissance in force around Tirnovo, 70 miles (110 km) to the south, and they brought word back that the Turks were indeed coming.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Word also reached the besieged inhabitants of Nicopolis, who blew horns and cheered.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Boucicaut claimed the noise of their celebration was a ruse as he believed that the Sultan would never attack; he further threatened to cut off the ears of anyone who discussed rumors of the Turks' approach as being damaging to the morale of the crusaders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] One of the few to concern himself with scouting the situation was de Coucy, who took a group of 500 knights and 500 mounted archers south.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Learning of a large group of Turks approaching through a nearby pass, he separated 200 horsemen to carry out a feint retreat, drawing the pursuing Turks into an ambush where the rest of his men, waiting concealed, attacked their rear.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Giving no quarter, de Coucy's men killed as many as they could and returned to the camp where his action shook the camp from its lethargy and drew the admiration of the other crusaders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Tuchman argues that it also increased the overconfidence of the French and again drew the jealousy of D'Eu, who accused Coucy of risking the army out of recklessness and attempting to steal glory and authority from Nevers.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund claimed that this vanguard was not worthy of the attention of knights.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund proposed that, once the shock of first clash had passed, the French form the front line to rush in, while the Hungarians and the other allies follow to support the attack and keep the sipahis (Turkish heavy cavalry) from sweeping around the crusaders' flanks.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] D'Eu denounced the proposal as demeaning to the knights, who would be forced to follow peasant footmen into battle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] He reportedly stated, "To take up the rear is to dishonor us, and expose us to the contempt of all" and declared that he would claim front place as Constable and anyone in front of him would do him mortal insult.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In this he was supported by Boucicaut; Nevers, reassured by the confidence of the younger French lords, was easily convinced.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] With the French set on a charge, Sigismund left to make a battle plan for his own forces.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Apparently within hours, he sent word to the camp that Bayezid was only six hours away.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The crusaders, said to be drunk over dinner, reacted in confusion; some refused to believe the report, some rose in panic, and some hastily prepared for battle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At this point, supposedly because of a lack of spare guards, the prisoners taken at Rachowa were massacred.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Even European chroniclers would later call this an act of "barbarism".
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At daybreak on 25 September the combatants began to organize themselves under the banners of their leaders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At this point, Sigismund sent his Grand Marshal to Nevers to report that his scouts had sighted the Turkish vanguard and asked for the offensive to be postponed for two hours, when his scouts would have returned with intelligence as to the numbers and disposition of the enemy.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevers summoned a hasty council of advisors, in which Coucy and Jean de Vienne, admiral of France and the eldest French knight on the crusade, advised obeying the wishes of the Hungarian king, which seemed wise to them.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At this, D'Eu declared that Sigismund simply wished to hoard the battle honors for himself and declared his willingness to lead the charge.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] D'Eu rejected any wait and the council fell into a fierce dispute, with the younger hawks charging that the elder knights were not prudent, but fearful.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The argument seems to have been settled when D'Eu decided to advance.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] D'Eu took control of the vanguard of the French knights, while Nevers and Coucy commanded the main body.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The French knights, accompanied by their mounted archers, rode out with their backs to Nicopolis to meet the Turks, who were descending the hills to the south.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Knights Hospitaler, Germans, and other allies stayed with the Hungarian forces under Sigismund.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The subsequent events are obscured by conflicting accounts.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Chroniclers write of horses impaled on stakes, riders dismounting, stakes being pulled up to allow horses through, and the eventual rout of the Turkish infantry, who fled behind the relative safety of the sipahis.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Coucy and Vienne recommended that the French pause to reform their ranks, give themselves some rest and allow the Hungarians time to advance to a position where they could support the French.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] They were overruled by the younger knights who, having no idea of the size of the Turkish force, believed that they had just defeated Bayezid's entire army and insisted on pursuit.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The French knights thus continued up the hill, though accounts state that more than half were on foot by this point, either because they had been unhorsed by the lines of sharpened stakes or had dismounted to pull up stakes.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Struggling in their heavy armor, they reached the plateau on the top of the slope, where they had expected to find fleeing Turkish forces, but instead found themselves facing a fresh corps of sipahis, whom Bayezid had kept in reserve.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] As the sipahis surged forward in the counterattack sounding trumpets, banging kettle drums and shouting the *Tekbir*, the French realized how desperate their situation was and some knights fled back down the slope.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The rest fought on, "no frothing boar nor enraged wolf more fiercely", in the words of one contemporary chronicler.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Admiral de Vienne, to whom was granted the honor as the eldest knight of carrying the French standard into battle, was wounded many times as he attempted to rally his countrymen before being struck down.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Other notable knights who were slain include Jean de Carrouges, Philippe de Bar, and Odard de Chasseron.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Turks threatened to overwhelm Nevers, and his bodyguard threw themselves to the ground in submission to plead for the life of their liege lord.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Notwithstanding the declaration of jihad, the Turks were as interested in the riches that could be gained by ransoming noble captives as anyone else, and took Nevers prisoner.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Seeing Nevers taken, the rest of the French yielded.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The timeline of events is hazy, but it appears that as the French were advancing up the slope, sipahis were sweeping down along the flanks in an envelopment.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund, the Master of Rhodes, and the Germans fought to prevent the envelopment with "unspeakable massacre" on both sides.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At this point, the Turks received a reinforcement of 1,500 Serbian knights under the command of Stefan Lazarević, which proved critical.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Convinced to flee, Sigismund and the Master managed to escape on a fisherman's boat to the Venetian ships in the Danube.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Count Hermann of Cilli, governor of Habsburg Carniola and a cousin of Sigismund's deceased wife, led the force that allowed the escape and would later become the king's father-in-law.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Bayezid and his vassal Stefan Lazarević recognized Nicholas II Garai, Lazarević's brother-in-law, fighting on Sigismund's side.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A deal was made, and Sigismund's army surrendered, completing their defeat in detail.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund would later state to the Hospitaller Master, "We lost the day by the pride and vanity of these French.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] If they believed my advice, we had enough men to fight our enemies." Chronicler Jean Froissart would declare.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Bayezid toured the battlefield later that day, hoping to find the corpse of the King of Hungary.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] His rage was only heightened by the discovery of the massacred prisoners from Rahovo.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] He ordered all of the prisoners assembled before him the following morning (26 September).
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Turks recognized Jacques de Helly, a French knight who had served under Murad I, and had him identify the chief nobles for ransom.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Coucy, Bar, D'Eu, Gui de La Tremoïlle and several others were grouped with Nevers to be spared.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Those judged to be under the age of 20 were taken as slaves by the Turks.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The rest, thought to number several thousand, were bound together in groups of three or four and had their hands tied to be marched naked before the Sultan.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Ordered to proceed, a group of executioners proceeded to kill each group in turn, either by decapitation or by severing their limbs from the body.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Nevers and the rest of the noble captives were forced to stand beside Bayezid and watch the executions.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Jean Le Maingre, called "Boucicaut", was recognized in the line, and Nevers fell to his knees before the Sultan and indicated with intertwined fingers that they were like brothers.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Thus convinced that Boucicaut was worth a noble ransom, he was spared and grouped with the other high nobles.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The killing continued from early morning until late afternoon, at which point Bayezid, either himself sickened by the bloodshed or convinced by his ministers that he was unnecessarily enraging Christendom against him, called off the executioners.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Leaving aside the more hyperbolic account, the number of dead is said to have ranged from 300 to 3,000, though the number of dead on the battlefield was much more.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Of those who fled the battlefield, few survived.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] So many attempted to swim to the boats in the Danube that several sank from the load; afterward, those on the boats pushed away those trying to board.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Many who attempted to swim all the way across the river drowned.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund, fearful of Wallachian treachery, sailed to the Black Sea and Constantinople before making his way home by sea.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Those Crusaders who made it across the Danube and tried to return home by land found that the land they were traveling over had already been stripped of forage by the retreating force of Wallachians.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Reduced to wandering through the woods in rags and robbed of whatever possessions they had, many of the starved survivors died along the way.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Perhaps the most famous of the few who reached home after this journey was Count Rupert of Bavaria (Ruprecht Pipan), eldest son of the future King Rupert of Germany, who arrived at his doorstep in beggar's rags and died several days later from his trials.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The captives were forced to march the 350-mile length to Gallipoli, stripped of clothing down to their shirts and most without shoes, with hands tied and beaten by their captors.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] At Gallipoli, the noble captives were kept in the upper rooms of a tower while the 300 prisoners that were the Sultan's share of the common captives were kept below.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The ship carrying Sigismund passed within half a mile of the tower as it went through the Hellespont, for which the Turks lined the captives along the shore and mockingly called out for Sigismund to come and rescue his comrades.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Sigismund, while in Constantinople, had made overtures to ransom the captives, but Bayezid was aware that Hungary's wealth had been depleted in the crusade and that richer ransoms could be had from France.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] After two months in Gallipoli, the prisoners were transferred to Bursa, the joint Ottoman capital located in Asia, where they awaited word of their ransom.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In the first week of December, rumors of unimaginable defeat arrived in Paris.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] As no certain news was to be had, rumor-mongers were imprisoned in the Grand Châtelet and, if convicted of lying, sentenced to death by drowning.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The King, Burgundy, Orleans and the Duke of Bar all sped envoys to Venice and Hungary to bring word back.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] On 16 December merchant ships brought word to Venice of defeat at Nicopolis and the escape of Sigismund.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Jacques de Helly, the knight who had identified the nobles after the battle, had been charged by Bayezid, under his vow to return, to inform the King of France and Duke of Burgundy of his victory and demands for ransom.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] On Christmas, de Helly rode into Paris and, kneeling before the king, recounted the expedition, the battle, defeat and Bayezid's massacre of the prisoners.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] He also carried letters from Nevers and the other noble captives.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Those for whom he did not carry letters were assumed to be dead, and weeping members of the court gathered around de Helly to seek more information about loved ones.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Denis, "affliction reigned in all hearts" and Deschamps wrote of "funerals from morning to eve".
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A delegation with rich gifts for Bayezid left Paris on 20 January 1397 to negotiate the ransoms.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] De Helly, bound by his oath to return, had already departed with letters for the captives.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Gian Galeazzo's help became vital, as he had extensive contacts in the Ottoman court.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Envoys were sent informing him of belated approval by the King allowing the fleur-de-lis to be added to the Visconti escutcheon, Galeazzo's first wife having been from the French royal house, and to make every effort to gain his assistance.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Meanwhile, those envoys sent in early December had reached Venice and, having learned of the fate of the captives, were attempting to make their way to Bursa.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Venice, which was the French conduit to the Muslim east due to her trade network, became the center for exchange of news, cash and ransomed captives.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] On 13 February 1397, de Coucy, ill and perhaps suffering from battle wounds, died.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Released on their own accord to seek funds in the Levant, Boucicaut and Guy de Tremoille reached Rhodes, where de Tremoille fell ill and died around Easter.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] French negotiators in the Sultan's court finally reached agreement on a ransom of 200,000 gold florins in June.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] With a down payment of 75,000, the prisoners were released on 24 June on their promise to stay in Venice until the rest of the ransom was paid.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] However, the nobles found it unthinkable to travel in less than their accustomed splendor and borrowed nearly as much as the ransom amount in reprovisioning themselves.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Arriving in Venice in October after stopping in various islands to recover and borrow money, the financial transactions required to both provide the ransom and pay for the travel arrangements and living expenses of the nobles were tremendously complicated.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A three-sided transaction between Burgundy, Sigismund and Venice took 27 years to settle.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] A plague outbreak in Venice required the nobles to move temporarily to Treviso, but still claimed Henry of Bar.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The last of the Crusader leaders (Nevers, Boucicaut, Guillaume de Tremoille and Jacques de la Marche), along with seven or eight other knights, re-entered France in February 1398.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] With a historian's hindsight Johan Huizinga remarked upon "the lamentable consequences of statecraft recklessly embarking on an enterprise of vital import in the spirit of a chivalrous adventure", though participants and contemporary chroniclers did not analyse the event in these terms.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] After this defeat, Western Europe made no further moves to stop the Turkish advance in the Balkans until the 1440s.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] England and France soon renewed their war.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Wallachia continued its stance against the Ottomans, repelling expeditions in 1397 and 1400.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] In 1402 Sultan Bayezid I was defeated and captured by Timur (Tamerlane), and Mircea cel Batran and the Kingdom of Hungary took advantage of the resulting anarchy to campaign against the Ottomans.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] The Battle of Nicopolis is also widely regarded as the end of the Second Bulgarian Empire, since hopes for its revival had come to an end with the defeat of the Crusaders.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] Its last ruler, Ivan Sratsimir of Bulgaria, was captured and killed in Bursa.
[src:baba-vida/battle-of-nicopolis] By their victory at Nicopolis, the Turks discouraged the formation of future European coalitions against them.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] It is one of the best-preserved strongholds in Bulgaria and a cultural monument of national importance.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The fortress's walls are over 2 metres (6.6 ft) thick in the foundation and reaching up to 12 m (39 ft) in height.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] Three separate fortified yards exist that are connected with each other through gates.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The fortress has a total area of 10,210 square metres (109,900 sq ft).
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The Belogradchik Fortress was reconstructed to later become a proclaimed cultural monument.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] It is managed by the local historical museum authority.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The initial fortress was constructed during the time when the region was part of the Roman Empire.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The rock formations in the area served as a natural protection, as fortified walls were practically only built from the northwest and southeast, with the yard being surrounded by rocks up to 70 m (230 ft) high from the other sides.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] Initially, the Belogradchik Fortress served for surveillance and not strictly defense.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The Bulgarian tsar of Vidin, Ivan Stratsimir extended the old fortress in the 14th century, building fortified garrisons in front of the existing rock massifs.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] During Stratsimir's rule, the Belogradchik Fortress became one of the most important strongholds in the region, second only to the tsar's capital fortress of Vidin, Baba Vida.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] During the Ottoman conquest of Bulgaria, the fortress was captured by the Ottomans in 1396.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] They were forced to further expand the stronghold due to the intensified hajduk and insurrectionist activity in the region.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] Considerable changes to the fortress were made in the early 19th century.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] These changes were typical for the Ottoman castle architecture of the period, a full reorganization being carried out, as well as additional expansion.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] Typically European elements were added to the Belogradchik Fortress owing to the French and Italian engineers that participated in the expansion.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] The stronghold had an important role in the Ottoman suppression of the Bulgarian Belogradchik Uprising of 1850.
[src:baba-vida/belogradchik-fortress] It was last used in warfare during the Serbo-Bulgarian War in 1885.
